comments.text: @chrisrollins7413  I get that, but aren't you worried that at some point you will have no idea what your codebase is really doing, and only aware of what your code is spitting out? I feel that Cursor is more of a pair-programmer, whereas Claude Code is an assistant that does everything for you. The latter definitely makes everything easy, just sit back and write prompts, but the former allows you to be in the driver seat incase things need human oversight.
comments.author: @ForxiaPrime

comments.text: ​ @ForxiaPrime  I use Claude Code as a pair programmer and I'm a professional SWE, you can also use it for small stuff, there's no need to have claude code implement everything from zero. You can write recipes md files and give it to him to feed on how to create a component for example and pass on clear instructions of what you want to add. If your code base is strongly typed and have a good structure it will usually output a flawless component and you'll save tons of time. It's on another level compared to Cursor/Cline etc. You can also tackle complex troubleshooting all in one tool.

comments.text: I disagree, you can get a huge performance boost on Claude Code if you are a good programmer as well using md files to guide the implementation. Otherwise you'll be losing productivity.
